"Beddington, London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":29,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Dalingridge was born about 1426, in Beddington, London, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Walter Dallingridge, was 68 and her mother, Margaret de Chamond, was 52. She married Sir Humphrey de Bohun in 1446, in England. She died in Fressingfield, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1426–":"umbes 1426–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1398–1421":"1398–1421","1400–1443":"1400–1443","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1420–1502":"1420–1502","1418–1468":"1418–1468","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud"